## Risk Rating: Medium

No confirmed compromise, but PowerShell abuse is a common precursor to payload delivery, persistence, and lateral movement in real intrusions. Rated on technique risk (LOLBin abuse potential) rather than confirmed outcome.

## Recommendations

- Enable PowerShell Script Block Logging (Event ID 4104) and Module Logging org-wide if not already on.
- Set PowerShell execution policy to restrict unsigned/remote scripts where feasible.
- Deploy application control (e.g., WDAC/AppLocker) to limit PowerShell usage to authorized admin contexts.
- Alert on known-suspicious command patterns (`-enc`, `-w hidden`, `IEX (New-Object Net.WebClient)`, etc.).
- Correlate PowerShell alerts with EDR process-tree data for faster triage.
- Isolate/rescan the host if any persistence indicators are found on follow-up review.

## Detection Query Example (KQL)

```kql
DeviceProcessEvents
| where FileName =~ "powershell.exe"
| where ProcessCommandLine has_any ("-enc", "-EncodedCommand", "-w hidden", "-WindowStyle Hidden", "IEX", "DownloadString")
| project Timestamp, DeviceName, AccountName, ProcessCommandLine, InitiatingProcessFileName
```

